		<div class="styleguide-annotation">
			<h1>Buttons</h1>
			<dl>
				<dt>About Buttons</dt>
				<dd>
					<p>Buttons are largely governed by <a href="#theming">theming</a>, and as a result do not offer much in terms of customization via <b>data-*</b> attributes.</p>
				</dd>
				<dt>Button Options</dt>
				<dd>
					<p><b>data-loadable=&quot;true&quot;</b> Only applicable to &lt;a&gt; and &lt;button&gt; tags due to the need to alter the innerHTML property (self closing &lt;input /&gt; tags can not have any markup within), loadable adds a subtle animation to the button when clicked, useful in conjunction with buttons that trigger AJAX requests or some other backgrounded process that needs waiting time. While the animation is triggered automatically when the button is clicked, it is up to the developer to stop the animation (if necessary) by simply removing the <b>thinking</b> class that is applied. Alternatively, and suggested, the developer may trigger one of [loader:toggle, loader:toggle:on, loader:toggle:off] events on the jQuery instance of the element. Triggering events are preferred as other properties on the button are also made when the animation is triggered, such as disabling the button when the animation is active, and re-enabling it when not active.</p>
				</dd>
			</dd>
		</div>
