		<div class="styleguide-annotation">
			<h1>Maps</h1>
			<dl>
				<dt>About Maps</dt>
				<dd>
					<p>Maps make it easier to quickly generate customized Google maps as well as tie them to user input, as in the case of <b>data-location</b>. Each map instantiated via the use of <b>data-location</b> will have two hidden input elements appended immediately following the input field the attribute is applied to. The two elements will receive the latitude and longitude of the current address displayed in the map. Or, in the case of a draggable pin/marker, the lat/long of that. The name of these elements will by default share the name of the input field <b>data-location</b> is found on, suffixed by &quot;[latitude]&quot; and &quot;[longitude]&quot; respectively. If the name of the input element matches the format &quot;xxxxxx[yyyyy]&quot;, the &quot;[yyyyy]&quot; portion will be stripped, leaving either &quot;xxxxxx[latitude]&quot; or &quot;xxxxxx[longitude]&quot;. If the value of &quot;xxxxxx&quot; needs to be different than the default, it can be controlled via the <b>data-prefix</b> attribute, see options below.</p>
				</dd>
				<dt>Map Options</dt>
				<dd>
					<p><b>data-address=&quot;&lt;address&gt;&quot;</b> Specify an address that should be loaded into the element this attribute is applied to (usually a div). The map size is dependent on the size of the element <b>data-address</b> is applied to, and should be handled separately.</p>
					<p><b>data-location=&quot;selector&quot;</b> Applicable to &lt;input /&gt; fields only, ties the input field to a map that will render within the element matched by the provided jQuery selector. When the input is blurred or the enter key is pressed, the map will update with the address that was entered (if found, otherwise returns to default grayscale zoomed out map.) The input field will also receive address autocompletion.</p>
					<p><b>data-zoom=&quot;&lt;zoom level&gt;&quot;</b> Defaults to &quot;auto&quot; Provides a zoom level (1 - 20, 1 being the world, 20 being building level) that the map should default to when an address is loaded. In the case of <b>data-location</b> this zoom level will be applied whenever the address changes, regardless of what zoom level the user was at before.</p>
					<p><b>data-scroll=&quot;true/false&quot;</b> Defaults to false. Whether to allow scroll wheel zooming when hovering over the map area.</p>
					<p><b>data-move=&quot;true/false&quot;</b> Defaults to false. Whether to allow the user to click and drag the map to move it around. If false, the map will essentially be static. Useful in conjunction with <b>data-zoom</b> to quickly render static, &quot;view-only&quot; maps.</p>
					<p><b>data-drag=&quot;true/false&quot;</b> Defaults to false. Used only in conjunction with <b>data-location</b>, whether or not to allow dragging and dropping of the location &quot;pin&quot; within the map.</p>
					<p><b>data-prefix=&quot;&lt;name&gt;&quot;</b> Defaults to the name attribute of the &lt;input /&gt; element, stripped of any trailing text matching the regex <b>/\[[A-Z0-9_]+\]/i</b> (i.e. - if name is "address[place]" the prefix will be "address"). Only applies to <b>data-location</b> attribute, specifies the prefix for the two dynamically generated lat/long hidden input field names.</p>
				</dd>
			</dl>
